[Black "1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 e6 #1/2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4
{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... e6
{ This is the most common move in the database and is extremely natural. Black makes it clear that they want to develop quickly to punish White's unconventional development. The knight on c3 is arguably misplaced as you usually put the pawn on c4 before developing the knight.  Black has the option to develop the bishop to d6 to directly challenge White’s dark-squared bishop or to go to b4 to put direct pressure on the knight on c3. }
4. Nb5
{ The 2nd most common move in the database so will come as a surprise to some. If you look in ChessBase, you'll see the 4 most recent games were all played by me against 4 players above 2600.  Nb5 almost looks like a children's trick, hoping that Black will not notice the c7-pawn hanging, yet it has a sophisticated positional undertone. }
4... Bb4+ 5. c3 Ba5
{ White has many options here but if you're in the mood to trick your opponent, there is a dangerous trap that many of my opponents have fallen into. There was one online blitz tournament where 3 Grandmasters fell for the same trap in a row. }
6. e3
{ Despite the temptation, I recommend a more objective approach.   After  6.a4  a6  7.b4  many of my opponents have played 7...Bb6 and not lived to tell the tale:  7...Bb6  8.a5  axb5  9.axb6  .  You can try to save face with  9...Na6  but it's basically lost already. There are a few strong continuations.  10.Bxc7  Qd7  11.Be5  Taking the pawn and returning the bishop to e5 leaves White up a pawn with the bishop pair. Black's doubled pawns are certainly not helping their cause much as well. }
6... O-O 7. Nf3
{ Again, there are so many different moves from Black and it's impossible to cover every single idea but take note of the common developing ideas. }
7... Nh5
{ It's important to know how to react to ...Nh5 in these positions, there are many options. }
8. Bd3
{ White can give up the bishop pair but continue with rapid development. } *

