{ White has a lot more flexibility here and can proceed in many ways.  5.Bd3  is totally fine, but I'd like to propose a more aggressive approach. }
5. f3
{ There are many options here for Black but most of them lead to the same types of positions.  Black can be prophylactic and play  5...Bg6  ,  5...h5  or  5...h6  , but  5...e6  is the most logical and most common continuation. }
5... e6 6. g4 Bg6 7. h4
{ Black always has a choice of ...h6 and ...h5 in these positions. Let's see how each choice affects the dynamic of the position. }
7... h5 8. g5 Ng8 9. Qd2
{ White sets up a very sneaky trap here. The logical move  9...Bd6  gives White a nice advantage. }
9... Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Qh2
{ This is certainly not the first nor the last time that we will see the queen challenging the h2-b8 diagonal. This idea looks ridiculous but it is advantageous for White to go into an endgame due to Black's long-term weaknesses. }
11... Qxh2 12. Rxh2 Ne7 13. O-O-O
{ Black's kingside structure will be weak in the long term. } 13... b5 14. Nh3
Nd7 15. Nf4
{ White has the ability to slowly maneuver and capitalize off Black's pawn structure. The h5-pawn and Black’s light-squared bishop are clear targets. }
