1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4
{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... c5
{ I would say that 3...c5 is one of, if not, the most challenging move to the Jobava London system. Black aims to put immediate pressure on the center and avoid all closed positions that you normally get. It is crucial to respond appropriately! }
4. e4
{ Crazy complications ensue immediately. Although the computer gives zeros everywhere, having more knowledge here will give you a significant advantage over your opponent.   4.e3  is the main move but it gives Black many options that are okay. I prefer to take a more direct approach and put Black to the test. }
4... dxe4 5. dxc5
{ I would say that  5...Nbd7  is by far the most logical move, but one should be aware of other logical options. }
5... Nbd7 6. b4
{ 6.Bb5  e5  allows Black to develop normally. While this is equal, the key point is to force Black to make difficult decisions. }
6... e5 7. Bg5 Be7 8. Bc4
{ This is where things start to get very interesting. Black has a few choices but all of them lead to chaos.  If you simply check this position with the engine, you'll see equality and move on, but since this position is so unfamiliar and imbalanced. Black often only equalizes after a long sequence of only moves that aren't intuitive to even the strongest humans. }
8... b6 9. Bd5 Rb8 10. c6 Bxb4
{ I think it should be clear why 3...c5 is one of the biggest challenges. You can't really play the same natural moves. However, things become extremely complex and you can show some really interesting preparation. }
11. Ne2 Nc5
{ This is a very logical move that most humans might play. However, this is where White has a chance to capitalize. }
12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. O-O
{ Although castling queenside in the other line looked pretty cool, the king is much safer on the kingside. White's improved king safety allows for Black's comprised structure and king safety to be punished. }
13... Be6 14. Qc1 f5 15. Qh6
{ White has a raging attack here. The details don't exactly matter here, but it's clear that Black is in trouble. }
