1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4
{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... c5
{ I would say that 3...c5 is one of, if not, the most challenging move to the Jobava London system. Black aims to put immediate pressure on the center and avoid all closed positions that you normally get. It is crucial to respond appropriately! }
4. e4
{ Crazy complications ensue immediately. Although the computer gives zeros everywhere, having more knowledge here will give you a significant advantage over your opponent.   4.e3  is the main move but it gives Black many options that are okay. I prefer to take a more direct approach and put Black to the test. }
4... Nxe4
{ 4...Nxe4 is arguably the best in response to 3.e4 as it leads to a somewhat dry endgame. However, I've analyzed this endgame very deeply and it is pleasant for White and very easy to play. Let's see how things progress. }
5. Nxe4 dxe4 6. dxc5
{ There are many interesting options here but 6...Qa5 is the most natural by far. }
6... Qxd1+ 7. Rxd1 Bd7 8. Be3 { A prophylactic move, preparing to play b4. }
8... e5
{ This is critical for Black to equalize, otherwise White has an advantage. }
9. Bc4 f5 10. g3
{ The advance of Black's pawn is halted, now White has the time to develop. Once developed, the queenside majority can slowly be advanced. }
10... Nc6 11. Ne2
{ Black has a few naturally developing moves, the order of them doesn't matter much. The point is to illustrate White's plan. }
11... Be7 12. h4
{ It's very important to prevent ...g5, to keep the central pawns in place. }
12... O-O-O 13. a3
{ Preparing b4 and thereby provoking ...a5, which would weaken the b6-square. }
13... a5 14. Bg5
{ White is ready to put some more pressure. Trading these bishops is crucial. The next point is to improve the knight and coordinate the rooks. Yet again, White has a clear path with extending on the queenside while Black is sort of unsure of what to do with the central pawns. }
