[Black "1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 a6 #1/5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4
{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... a6
{ I wouldn't say that 3...a6 is as directly challenging as other moves. However, it is very common among top-level grandmasters and makes for some really interesting chess.  The structures that we get here will be a bit different from the other positions because Nb5 is totally out of the question. Since the position will be closed in most outcomes, you can count on g4 and h4 being viable options. }
4. e3
{ This is the first major crossroad and Black's next move will dictate the dynamic of the position. }
4... c5
{ 4...c5 is just a worse version of 3...c5 @@StartBracket@@chapter 3@@EndBracket@@. I would regard this as directly critical but of course, some precision is required.   4...Bf5  5.Nf3  transposes to a position we have reached in chapter 1 after 3...a6. }
5. dxc5
{ The funny thing about this position is the  5...Nc6  is the most popular by far, then  5...e6  , and then  5...Qa5  .  5...Qa5  is the only move that is close to equality while  5...e6  and  5...Nc6  give White an edge. If that doesn't seem like an opportunity to catch your opponents, then I don't know what is. }
5... Nc6
{ Low and behold the most common move, played by Carlsen, Duda, Fressinet, and many more top GMs. Funnily enough, the computer gives a +.65 evaluation. There seems to be a common misconception in the current state of theory. I wonder if this hole could be exploited... }
6. a3 { a3 prepares b4. It is crucial to protect the c5-pawn! } 6... e5 7. Bg5
d4 8. exd4 Nxd4 9. b4 { White is up a pawn and has the compensation. } 9... b6
{ The only move to not be basically lost immediately. } 10. Nf3 bxc5 11. Bc4
{ Black has many options here but all of which give White a significant advantage. I will go through the most logical ones. }
11... Be7 12. Nxe5 O-O 13. O-O Bf5
{ Black is doing a good job of creating counterplay but White can retain the advantage with precise play. }
14. Be3 Nxc2 15. Qxd8 Bxd8 16. Bxc5 Nxa1 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 18. Rxa1
{ White is up a pawn and this will be very difficult to defend. If you let the position run on a very strong computer you might be able to hold but for 2 humans the most likely result is 1-0. }
*

