[Black "Pirc 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 d6 #1/2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 g6
{ White has many ways to secure a comfortable advantage. Although the central focus of the Moke London is 3.Bf4, it is important to note that this isn't forced and that White has different options. }
3. e4 d6
{ There are so many different setups for White here but I prefer to keep it simple. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Be2
{ This might not be the most eye-catching idea, but White has a very simple plan in mind. It is clear that White has central control as the d4- and e4-pawns remain uncontested. White will simply complete development and show that Black's position is inferior. }
5... O-O 6. O-O
{ Black has many different setups here so it's important to know how to respond appropriately but the ideas are more or less the same. I would say that this is the first critical position in this line and I have shown how to react against the main moves. Some lines are very concrete, but in most of the lines, it's important to know the developmental plans. }
6... c6
{ 6...c6 is the most common move in the database but it isn't really that challenging. It is critical to take space on the queenside! }
7. a4 a5
{ Black can start with ...a5 as well, but h3+Be3 is going to the main idea regardless. }
8. h3 Qc7 9. Be3
{ White's position is amazing. White still has central control, all of White's pieces are on great squares. Qd2 will come next and the rooks will be brought into the game. }
9... Nbd7 10. Qd2 e5
{ This is another example of an appropriate time to capture! } 11. dxe5 Nxe5
{ Black can recapture the pawn with the knight, but this leaves the d6-pawn very weak. }
12. Rad1 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Ne8 14. b3
{ b3 is a very nice consolidating move, simply asking Black to find a productive move. Black's position is very ugly; the knight on e8 is extremely passive. }
