[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "1.d4 d5 2.Nc3 Bf5 #1/2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ The main move order that I have shown in the Moke London is after 1...Nf6. However, 1...d5 is another important order to consider. In most cases, it transposes, however, it is important to be aware of when it doesn't transpose. }
2. Nc3
{ I recommend this move order because the goal is to make sure that moves other than 2...Nf6 aren't optimal. }
2... Bf5
{ Black can take the opportunity to develop the c8-bishop immediately, this variation is critical! }
3. f3
{ The early ...Bf5 gives us an opportunity to continue with rapid development! }
3... Nf6 4. g4 Bg6 5. g5 Nh5 6. e4 dxe4 7. f4
{ Black's knight on h5 is almost trapped. If Black does not know the best move here, the game could end very quickly. }
7... e5
{ 7...e5 has only been played in 2 games and even more precise play is demanded afterwards.   7...h6  might look natural but White can win a piece now:  8.f5  Bxf5  9.Qxh5  Qxd4  . You might be concerned here as Black has 3 pawns for the piece, however, White retains a significant initiative.  10.Qe2  White prepares Be3 and castles, Black is under immediate pressure.  10...Nc6  11.Be3  Qe5  12.O-O-O  Black's king is not safe in the center and the e5-queen is slightly awkward.  12...Rd8  13.Rxd8+  Nxd8  14.gxh6  The dust has settled and White is up a piece for 2 pawns at the moment. White also retains an initiative!   7...e6  is another natural developing move but the knight is trapped on h5.  8.Be2!  There is no way for the knight to escape.  8...Nf6  9.gxf6  gxf6  10.Be3  Black sacrificed the piece back for 2 pawns but it doesn't do much. White will play Qd2 and castle and continue the initiative. Black's 2 pawns aren't sufficient compensation for the piece due to White's activity. }
8. fxe5 Nc6 9. Be3 Bb4 10. Be2 Ne7
{ This has never been played but it is has been analyzed in the cloud. I would say that the chances of this appearing on the board are slim to none. }
11. Bxh5 Nd5
{ White is up a full piece but Black's pieces coordinate very well. } 12. Bxg6
Nxe3 13. Qd2 Qxg5
{ It is important to delay ...Bxc3 as it gives White fewer options. } 14. Bxe4
Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Qh4+ 16. Kd2 Qxe4 17. Ne2
{ The position has simplified a bit and White seems to be out of the woods. }
17... Nd5 18. Qd3
{ Black has a few logical queen moves that equalize. Black has equalized but there is still plenty of chess to be played. }
*

