[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ I couldn't make this a Lifetime Repertoire without going into the Dutch. I've personally never been afraid of the Dutch and I don't think you should be either. The Dutch is very uncommon for me to face in classical chess but I face it infrequently in online games.  I think I can safely say that the Dutch is not a direct challenge to the Jobava London but it's important to know how to play against it. There are many setups but I'm going to recommend one that has a similar developmental style. }
2. Nc3 { It wouldn't be a Jobava London without bringing the knight to c3. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4
{ You might think that we wouldn't go for the traditional setup but this is where we really get to have some fun. If you've been paying attention to the common themes, you might guess our next move. }
3... e6 4. g4
{ This will definitely provoke an eyebrow raise or two. This idea might look crazy but it's actually the first choice of the engine. White aims to go for the immediate initiative, the g-pawn is a small price to pay.  There are a few logical ways for Black to respond but the ideas are pretty similar. }
4... d5
{ 4...d5  is a logical response, continuing to take space in the center, but let's wait to get a comfortable position. }
5. gxf5 { White does not miss the opportunity to trade the g- for the e-pawn. }
5... exf5 6. e3
{ One can approach White's advantage here from a structural perspective. The biggest challenge this general setup is Black playing ...c5 and immediately challenging the center.  However, now that we have traded the g- and e-pawns, Black's center has been weakened while White has opened the kingside. Therefore, Black's central pressure is significantly weaker while White has very natural play on the kingside. }
6... Bb4
{ White has a consistent response against ...Bb4 in these Dutch structures in particular. In other lines, we are afraid to let our opponent double our pawns but in this case, we're encouraging it! }
7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3
{ White's pawns might be doubled but the f4-bishop dominates the dark squares unchallenged. It's not easy for Black to target the c3-pawn. White also has a very safe place for the king on f2! }
8... O-O 9. h4 { White's idea will be revealed soon. } 9... Nbd7 10. h5 c5 11.
h6 g6 12. f3
{ White's king is ready to hide on f2 and can even go to d2 in certain variations. }
