1. d4 g6
{ 1...g6 is one of the moves where we don't necessarily get the typical Jobava London position but the move itself is slightly dubious.  One should note that I won't cover many of the major setups here as they have been covered in the 2...g6 setup. I will cover the setups that don't lead to transpositions.  On the bright side, there aren't that many which keeps our approach against the Modern pretty simple.   1...Nf6  2.Nc3  g6  3.e4  d6  leads to the most common modern setup and has already been covered. }
2. e4 Bg7 3. Nf3
{ As much as it pains me to not bring the knight to c3, this move order avoids many other setups and keeps things extremely simple. }
3... d6 { 3...c5  4.d5  d6  5.Nc3  Nf6  6.Bc4  is yet another transposition. }
4. Nc3 a6
{ The most logical path,  4...Nf6  , transposes to the 2...g6 chapter.  I've really tried to simplify things. }
5. a4 b6
{ Black can avoid the transposition with ...b6 which is actually the most common move in the database. In this case, we're going to go for a very direct approach. }
6. h4
{ Putting immediate pressure on Black, forcing our opponents to decide how to respond. The move ...b6 has actually made h4 stronger as the open h1-a8 diagonal gives White more tactical possibilities. }
6... h6 7. Bc4 e6 8. d5
{ We are taking an extremely positional approach here. The point is to provoke ...e5. }
8... e5 9. h5 g5 10. Nd2
{ We have created a hole on f5 and weakened the light squares. This idea is truly very beautiful, d5 and h5 were perfectly timed to provoke the structural weaknesses. If ...f5 isn't played, things get ugly. }
10... f5 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. Nde4
{ The e5 outpost is great and Black's position has many holes. White retains a significant advantage. }
