1. d4 c5
{ I really wanted to make this a Lifetime Repertoire so I have decided to go into serious detail to cover all of the responses from 1.d4. The Moke London is an essential part of my repertoire, especially in online events. I scored wins against Duda and Kosteniuk recently in the Airthings Masters.  1...c5 is a relatively common response that we should cover. I don't consider 1...c5 a threat to the repertoire at all and I will show you how to secure a significant advantage! }
2. d5
{ This ...c5, d5 exchange is pretty common. White takes space by playing d5 and prepares to take even more central space. I will cover the main setups here, but the general ideas remain the same. }
2... e5
{ Interestingly enough, 2...e5 is the most popular move in the database but the computer already gives an edge of 1.6. That is already an indication that we are not worried at all about this deviation from the Moke London. }
3. e4 d6 4. Nc3
{ White has a very simple plan here: the knight on g1 belongs on c4. If White can put the knight there then all of White's play is very natural. Let's see that plan in action.  There are many different moves here but I don't think it's important to go into extreme depth here. The computer is giving a 1.6 advantage for a reason, thus, it's important to know the developmental plans. }
4... a6
{ Black can include the move ...a6 before developing, it is crucial to respond with a4 and then the same developmental plans apply. }
5. a4 Be7 6. Nf3 Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Bg5 9. Bxg5 Qxg5 10. Qg4
{ The same idea applies here with the moves ...a6 and a4 included. Those moves would be included anyway so it doesn't make a huge difference. }
