{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... e6
{ 3...e6 is the most common move in the database and is extremely natural. Black makes it clear that they want to develop quickly to punish White's unconventional development. The knight on c3 is arguably misplaced as you usually put the pawn on c4 before developing the knight.  Black has the option to develop the bishop to d6 to directly challenge White’s dark-squared bishop or to go to b4 to put direct pressure on the knight on c3. }
4. Nb5
{ 4.Nb5  is the 2nd most common move in the database so will come as a surprise to some. If you look in ChessBase, you'll see the 4 most recent games were all played by me against 4 players above 2600.   Nb5  almost looks like a children's trick, hoping that Black will not notice the c7-pawn hanging, yet it has a sophisticated positional undertone. }
4... Bb4+ 5. c3 Ba5
{ White has many options here but if you're in the mood to trick your opponent, there is a dangerous trap that many of my opponents have fallen into. There was one online blitz tournament where 3 Grandmasters fell for the same trap in a row. }
6. e3
{ Despite the temptation, I recommend a more objective approach.   After  6.a4  a6  7.b4  many of my opponents have played 7...Bb6 and not lived to tell the tale:  7...Bb6  8.a5  axb5  9.axb6  .  You can try to save face with  9...Na6  but it's basically lost already. There are a few strong continuations.  10.Bxc7  Qd7  11.Be5  Taking the pawn and returning the bishop to e5 leaves White up a pawn with the bishop pair. Black's doubled pawns are certainly not helping their cause much as well. }
6... O-O 7. Nf3
{ Again, there are so many different moves from Black and it's impossible to cover every single idea but take note of the common developing ideas. }
7... Nbd7 8. Be2
{ White just continues with natural developing moves. There's no need to do anything fancy.   One might wonder why the bishop goes to e2 instead of d3 like in the previous variation; I will show you the difference:   8.Bd3  a6  9.Na3  c5  10.dxc5  Nxc5  11.b4  . In this position, Black can take on d3. If the bishop would have been on e2 instead, b4 would have won a piece.  If Black can't play ...a6 and ...c5 immediately, then we don't face any immediate pressure. }
8... c6 9. Na3 Qe7 10. Qa4 Bd8 11. h3 b5 12. Qc2 a6 13. Nb1
{ White has almost completed natural development. This is not just a specific line from a concrete perspective, but an important route to show regarding different developmental ideas. }
