[White "1) 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 e6"]
[Black "1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 e6 with 4...Bd6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4
{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... e6
{ 3...e6 is the most common move in the database and is extremely natural. Black makes it clear that they want to develop quickly to punish White's unconventional development. The knight on c3 is arguably misplaced as you usually put the pawn on c4 before developing the knight.  Black has the option to develop the bishop to d6 to directly challenge White’s dark-squared bishop or to go to b4 to put direct pressure on the knight on c3. }
4. Nb5
{ 4.Nb5  is the 2nd most common move in the database so will come as a surprise to some. If you look in ChessBase, you'll see the 4 most recent games were all played by me against 4 players above 2600.   Nb5  almost looks like a children's trick, hoping that Black will not notice the c7-pawn hanging, yet it has a sophisticated positional undertone. }
4... Bd6
{ This is a move that I have faced quite a lot in online games but it's far from challenging and gives White a comfortable advantage. }
5. Nxd6+ cxd6 6. e3 Qb6
{ White has the choice of retaining a positional advantage by playing  7.Rb1  or continuing the initiative with  7.Bd3  . Both are very strong. }
7. Rb1 O-O 8. c3 { It's important to consolidate the queenside structure. }
8... h6
{ The idea behind ...h6 is multi-purpose: it takes away the g5-square from White's dark-squared bishop so ...Nh5 could be an idea. }
9. h3 { White takes the time to create space for the bishop. } 9... Re8 10. Nf3
{ White will proceed with normal development and Be2, O-O and c4 is a potential pawn break as well. The position basically plays itself. }
10... Ne4 11. Bh2 Bd7 12. Qb3
{ 12.Qb3 forces black to make a decision. If Black ignores the queen then White can capture and double the b-pawns. Having doubled b- and d-pawns certainly won't be optimal.  It is likely that the black queen will step aside. White will finish development and castle with a comfortable advantage. }
