4. e3
{ 4.e3 keeps the momentum going and aims to take advantage of the bishop on f5. The position might look a bit dry here, but Black must be precise to fully equalize.  Black's three main choices are 4...a6, 4...c6 and 4...e6. The great thing about the opening is that against Black's most logical setups, you'll proceed with the same developmental ideas.   The move  4.f3  is quite common in blitz and I have played it a lot myself, but it leads to many complications that I believe are unnecessary. From an objective perspective, the engine also isn't a big fan. I'm sure Simon Williams would suggest this move, but I'd like to take a more principled approach. }
4... c6
{ White has a lot more flexibility here and can proceed in many ways.  5.Bd3  is totally fine, but I'd like to propose a more aggressive approach. }
5. f3
{ There are many options here for Black but most of them lead to the same types of positions.  Black can be prophylactic and play  5...Bg6  ,  5...h5  or  5...h6  , but  5...e6  is the most logical and most common continuation. }
5... h5
{ All of these different options might be scaring you but as I've said many times throughout this course, the concrete ideas are not that critical. I'm going through the different possibilities to show that in the large majority of cases, you're reaching specific structures where you're always playing the same ideas. }
6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. cxd3
{ The choice between capturing with the pawn and queen is something that must be explained very clearly.  In this case, White wants to take a more positional approach:Firstly, the h5-pawn is slightly overextended, thus, preventing Black from playing ...Nh5.Considering the fact that Black will most likely castle kingside, the h5-pawn could be used as a hook in a potential kingside attack.  Therefore, when White is able to provoke positional concessions like the ...h5 move, it makes sense to recapture with the pawn and take a positional approach.  However, if White has already committed on the kingside with g4 and h4, it's crucial to take with the queen as you'll end up castling queenside and need to maintain the initiative. }
7... e6 8. Nge2 h4 9. e4 Be7 10. Rc1
{ White prepares for any type of ...c5 break. Additionally, asking Black if they are willing to castle. It's a bit scary for Black to commit to castling before White because the h4-pawn could be used to open up the kingside. }
