1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4
{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... Bf5
{ 3...Bf5 is the second most played move in the database and one of the moves that I face very often when playing Grandmasters. Black takes the opportunity to develop the light-squared bishop before playing ...e6 so the bishop isn't stuck behind the pawn chain.  White has many options after this move but I have chosen the simplest. The entire point of the Jobava London system is to play positions where you are familiar with the common ideas and can proceed naturally. }
4. e3
{ 4.e3 keeps the momentum going and aims to take advantage of the bishop on f5. The position might look a bit dry here, but Black must be precise to fully equalize.  Black's three main choices are 4...a6, 4...c6 and 4...e6. The great thing about the opening is that against Black's most logical setups, you'll proceed with the same developmental ideas.   The move  4.f3  is quite common in blitz and I have played it a lot myself, but it leads to many complications that I believe are unnecessary. From an objective perspective, the engine also isn't a big fan. I'm sure Simon Williams would suggest this move, but I'd like to take a more principled approach. }
4... c6
{ White has a lot more flexibility here and can proceed in many ways.  5.Bd3  is totally fine, but I'd like to propose a more aggressive approach. }
5. f3
{ There are many options here for Black but most of them lead to the same types of positions.  Black can be prophylactic and play  5...Bg6  ,  5...h5  or  5...h6  , but  5...e6  is the most logical and most common continuation. }
5... e6 6. g4 Bg6 7. h4
{ Black always has a choice of ...h6 and ...h5 in these positions. Let's see how each choice affects the dynamic of the position. }
7... h6
{ 7...h6 is much less committal than 7...h5 but it still gives White an advantage and the ability to maintain the initiative with rapid development.  One should also note that this gives White the option to play h5. It might be tempting to play h5 before Bd3 but it's important to keep the pawn on h4 so you can play g5 later on and recapture with the pawn. }
8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Bd6
{ 9...Bd6 is the most popular move but it actually gives White a significant advantage. I even faced this move in an OTB game and didn't react appropriately. }
10. Nge2 Bxf4
{ I took with the pawn which isn't a bad move necessarily but there's absolutely no reason to double the pawns. }
11. Nxf4 Qd6 12. O-O-O Nbd7 13. g5
{ Black's king is still in the center and g5 puts significant pressure on the kingside. }
13... Ng8 14. Qd2
{ Qd2 indirectly protects the knight and prepares e4! g5 combined with e4 puts a lot of pressure on Black's position! }
14... Ne7 15. e4
{ I'd like to remind you that memorizing this concrete variation is not of the utmost importance. Rather, I'd like to illustrate the power of the combination of the g5- and e4-pawn breaks. Black's pieces are almost smothered, it's unclear what Black's knights are doing. Additionally, you'll see that Black usually maintains some degree of a lead in development. }
