[Round "?"]
[White "2) 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 Bf5"]
[Black "3.Bf4 Bf5 4.e3 a6 #3/11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4
{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... Bf5
{ 3...Bf5 is the second most played move in the database and one of the moves that I face very often when playing Grandmasters. Black takes the opportunity to develop the light-squared bishop before playing ...e6 so the bishop isn't stuck behind the pawn chain.  White has many options after this move but I have chosen the simplest. The entire point of the Jobava London system is to play positions where you are familiar with the common ideas and can proceed naturally. }
4. e3
{ 4.e3 keeps the momentum going and aims to take advantage of the bishop on f5. The position might look a bit dry here, but Black must be precise to fully equalize.  Black's three main choices are 4...a6, 4...c6 and 4...e6. The great thing about the opening is that against Black's most logical setups, you'll proceed with the same developmental ideas.   The move  4.f3  is quite common in blitz and I have played it a lot myself, but it leads to many complications that I believe are unnecessary. From an objective perspective, the engine also isn't a big fan. I'm sure Simon Williams would suggest this move, but I'd like to take a more principled approach. }
4... a6 5. Nf3
{ Against 4...a6, we don't go for the usual f3 and g4 plans. The reasoning behind this is that we want to fully capitalize on the fact that Black has spent a tempo playing ...a6.  In the variations with f3 and g4, ...a6 is a move that they want to have included. However, when we go for the idea with Nf3-Ne5, our opponents start to wonder if ...a6 was the most effective use of their time. }
5... Nbd7 6. Ne5
{ The important concept in this position is to understand if your next move will be Bd3 or g4. g4 is very committal so you need to be sure it's correct.  Against ...e6 and ...c6, it's appropriate to proceed with g4. However, if Black plays ...h6 or ...h5, it's appropriate to proceed with Bd3. }
6... h5
{ This is also possible but it's easy to conclude that it is just a worse version of 6...h6 after 7.Bd3. The pawn is clearly overextended on h5 and would be much better placed on h6. }
7. Bd3
{ If Black takes on d3, they accept a worse position. There are some interesting tries but they still lead to an advantage for White. }
7... e6 8. Bxf5 exf5 9. f3 { f3 prepares Qd3 and prevents ...Ne4. } 9... c6 10.
Qd3 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7
{ Black must sacrifice a pawn in the short term, certainly not an easy idea to find. Yet, White still maintains an advantage and initiative. }
12. Qxf5 g6 13. Qh3 Qe7 14. O-O-O g5 15. Bg3 Nxe5
{ This entire sequence is more or less forced. Let's see if White can break the position open. }
16. e4 Nc4 17. exd5 g4 18. fxg4 Bh6+ 19. g5 Bxg5+ 20. Kb1
{ I think forcing your opponent to make many difficult decisions and only moves up until move 20 is a success. Maybe that's just me. }
20... Qb4 { Let me remind you that all of these are only moves for Black. } 21.
b3
{ There are different ways to force a draw here but checking with the knight is the simplest. }
