1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4
{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... Bf5
{ 3...Bf5 is the second most played move in the database and one of the moves that I face very often when playing Grandmasters. Black takes the opportunity to develop the light-squared bishop before playing ...e6 so the bishop isn't stuck behind the pawn chain.  White has many options after this move but I have chosen the simplest. The entire point of the Jobava London system is to play positions where you are familiar with the common ideas and can proceed naturally. }
4. e3
{ 4.e3 keeps the momentum going and aims to take advantage of the bishop on f5. The position might look a bit dry here, but Black must be precise to fully equalize.  Black's three main choices are 4...a6, 4...c6 and 4...e6. The great thing about the opening is that against Black's most logical setups, you'll proceed with the same developmental ideas.   The move  4.f3  is quite common in blitz and I have played it a lot myself, but it leads to many complications that I believe are unnecessary. From an objective perspective, the engine also isn't a big fan. I'm sure Simon Williams would suggest this move, but I'd like to take a more principled approach. }
4... e6
{ 4...e6 is the most logical move as Black prepares to develop the dark-squared bishop and castle. It is also the most popular move in the database by a large margin. While ...a6 and ...c6 are important to consider, ...e6 should be considered critical and will certainly be the most common move you face. }
5. Bd3
{ 5.Bd3  forces Black to make a decision. The key in any opening is forcing your opponent to make difficult decisions, as any human is likely to falter at some point. Yet again, Black has many options. Black's flexibility shouldn't be something you fear, as you'll see Black's lack of a direct plan can make it easy for one to go wrong. }
5... c6
{ 5...c6 is the computer's #1 suggestion, but I even struggle to explain why. It is definitely not intuitive to play the moves ...a6 and ...c6 consecutively so I doubt that many of your opponents will proceed this way, but White can still put additional pressure. }
6. Nf3
{ It is important to maintain the tension to force Black to make a decision. Many players might falter and capture the bishop on d3 but this leads to White getting a comfortable decision. }
6... Bg6
{ Black always has the option to retreat and it's often a logical reply. Some opponents might be fearful of having doubled f-pawns. In this case, you can simply continue with natural development although h4 is a possibility as we saw in the previous line where Black played 5...Bg6 instead of 5...c6. }
7. O-O Nbd7 8. h3 Be7 9. Qe2
{ White prepares the e4-break and retains a slight advantage. Yet again, White is able to make very natural developing moves while forcing Black to make a few critical decisions. }
9... O-O 10. e4
{ This position already becomes a bit uncomfortable with e5 being a significant positional threat. }
10... dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Bxe4 13. Qxe4
{ Mass trades are forced but White retains a space advantage, solid center, and long term pressure. The pawn structure has transposed into a Caro-Kannesque position. White can play here without any risk. }
