6. h4
{ Black is already forced to be precise here as h5 will force Black to capture. You'll notice a common theme of wanting to recapture the bishop with the c-pawn and the positional concept behind this must be clearly understood.  The concept traces back to White's second move, 2.Nc3. It's extremely uncommon to develop the knight before pushing c4 and often prevents White from taking central control. So when you alleviate this central problem, White's structure improves significantly. }
6... Bxd3
{ Black can take immediately without forcing h5. But this lets White recapture with the c-pawn. }
7. cxd3
{ As I've explained more, the structure with the 2 doubled pawns is just very easy to play for White. The development is natural, you have different pawn breaks and there's always potential to attack on the kingside by pushing the h- and g-pawns. }
7... Bd6 8. Qb3
{ Responding to ...Bd6 with Qb3 for the second time. Without the bishop on d6 Black might defend the pawn by playing Qc8 but it's a bit awkward for Black here. }
8... Bxf4 9. Qxb7 Nbd7 10. exf4 c5 11. Nf3
{ We've seen this idea before but with the inclusion of the moves h5 and ...a6. }
11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nc5 13. Qc6+ Nfd7
{ Despite extremely accurate play from Black, White retains a small advantage with an eye-catching move. }
14. Rh3
{ It is clear that whenever a rook lift is an option, I recommend it. There are many interesting complications that I could get into but it's not under the purview of this course. White has forced Black to make a few critical decisions and got imbalanced where Black is totally unfamiliar. The goal is to take them into your jungle. }
