{ 5.Bd3  forces Black to make a decision. The key in any opening is forcing your opponent to make difficult decisions, as any human is likely to falter at some point. Yet again, Black has many options. Black's flexibility shouldn't be something you fear, as you'll see Black's lack of a direct plan can make it easy for one to go wrong. }
5... Bg6
{ 5...Bg6  immediately is also very natural but here we see some options to unleash some creative ideas. }
6. h4
{ Black is already forced to be precise here as h5 will force Black to capture. You'll notice a common theme of wanting to recapture the bishop with the c-pawn and the positional concept behind this must be clearly understood.  The concept traces back to White's second move, 2.Nc3. It's extremely uncommon to develop the knight before pushing c4 and often prevents White from taking central control. So when you alleviate this central problem, White's structure improves significantly. }
6... a6 7. h5 Bxd3 8. cxd3
{ Black must play ...h6 here as White getting the opportunity to play h6 would have serious positional consequences. Provoking ...g6 from Black would further weaken the dark squares, as the placement of the e6- and g6-pawns certainly won't be controlling the dark squares. }
8... h6 9. Nf3 Bd6
{ This is where some interesting complications ensue. There always seems to be a hidden danger in Black's position. }
10. Qb3
{ Black has many options here and it's difficult to understand which is correct. One natural continuation is Bxf4. }
10... Bxf4 11. Qxb7 Nbd7 12. exf4
{ Black must find the only move, 12...c5, to not give White a +1 advantage. }
12... c5 13. O-O O-O 14. g3
{ White will lose the pawn back on h5 but the queenside majority will be difficult to deal with. }
