[White "3) 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 c5"]
[Black "1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 c5 4.e4 cxd4 #1/10"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4
{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... c5
{ I would say that 3...c5 is one of, if not, the most challenging move to the Jobava London system. Black aims to put immediate pressure on the center and avoid all closed positions that you normally get. It is crucial to respond appropriately! }
4. e4
{ Crazy complications ensue immediately. Although the computer gives zeros everywhere, having more knowledge here will give you a significant advantage over your opponent.   4.e3  is the main move but it gives Black many options that are okay. I prefer to take a more direct approach and put Black to the test. }
4... cxd4
{ This is one of the most challenging lines in the entire opening. If Black is well prepared here, you are forced to go into an equal endgame.  However, 4...cxd4 has only been played 10 times in the database, and the moves that your opponent must play to fully equalize, have basically never been played. }
5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd7
{ 6...Bd7  isn't the only option but this leads to a very forcing line. } 7.
Bxc6 Bxc6 8. e5 Nd7 9. e6
{ This is the critical move of the entire variation. Sacrificing a pawn to stunt Black's kingside development. If White can take advantage of Black's king in the center then it can become extremely dangerous. Black must play a series of moves here to equalize. }
9... fxe6 10. Nf3 Qb6 11. Qd2
{ According to the computer, 3 moves equalize for Black now but all are incredibly unclear:  11...d4  ,  11...e5  and  11...g5  . That's why you must play this against Yasser Seirawan because he will not be giving up any pawns. }
11... e5 12. Bxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 d4 14. O-O-O
{ White willingly sacrifices a piece, as Black is totally undeveloped. Black must defend perfectly to have a chance at survival. }
14... dxc3 15. Qxc3 Qc7
{ This also holds but the following continuation is equally as insane as Rd8. }
16. f4 e6 17. Qh3 Be7 18. Rhe1
{ Bringing the final piece into the attack, preparing to break through! } 18...
Rc8
{ The scary thing for Black in this position is that White has so many different options. More than 5 moves are all equal. }
19. Re3 { Forcing Black to play yet another only move. } 19... g6 20. Nxg6
{ I can conclude here that the position remains extremely difficult to defend and that White has amazing attacking chances! }
