{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... c5
{ I would say that 3...c5 is one of, if not, the most challenging move to the Jobava London system. Black aims to put immediate pressure on the center and avoid all closed positions that you normally get. It is crucial to respond appropriately! }
4. e4
{ Crazy complications ensue immediately. Although the computer gives zeros everywhere, having more knowledge here will give you a significant advantage over your opponent.   4.e3  is the main move but it gives Black many options that are okay. I prefer to take a more direct approach and put Black to the test. }
4... dxe4 5. dxc5
{ I would say that  5...Nbd7  is by far the most logical move, but one should be aware of other logical options. }
5... Bd7 6. Nb5 Na6 7. Qd4 Bc6 8. Qc4
{ 6...Na6 and 7...Bc6 were both forced but now Black is faced with a difficult decision. Let me remind you that this is completely uncharted territory. I am the first person to analyze this on the cloud. This really shows that the Jobava London is relatively unexplored and has a lot of hidden potential. }
8... Qd5 9. Rd1 Qxc4 10. Bxc4 Nd7 11. b4
{ There's a common theme of White trying to consolidate the queenside pawns. In most cases, the way that Black challenges these pawns is not intuitive whatsoever. This is the perfect example. }
11... e5 12. Be3 { Casually sacrificing a rook is the only way to equalize. }
12... Nxb4 13. Nc7+ Kd8 14. Nxa8 Nxc2+ 15. Kd2 Nd4
{ Both 15...Nd4 and 15...Nxe3 equalize. 15...Nd4 gives White some interesting options. }
16. Ne2 Bxc5 17. Rb1
{ Black is still in only move territory and must continue to be very precise. }
17... b6 18. Rhd1
{ Black faces another difficult decision here and the key point is that taking the knight is incorrect. }
18... Bxa8 19. Nxd4 exd4 20. Bxd4 Bxd4 21. Ke2 Bc5 22. Bb5 a6 23. Rxd7+ Kc8 24.
Ba4 b5 25. Rd2 Kc7 26. Rc1 Kb6 27. Bb3
{ After some forced complications this position is reached. It's clear that White has the upper hand. Despite the computer giving equality, this is much easier to play as White from a practical perspective. }
