5. h3 Bg7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Be2
{ The computer is suggesting some weird expansion on the queenside but it's clear that White has a slight advantage and that 4...c6 is in no way challenging. It should also be noted that the most common moves are not correct at all. }
7... b5 8. O-O a5 9. a3
{ One might wonder why we don't play  9.a4  here as we did after 8...Nbd7. The answer is simple: the move ...a5 anticipates a4 as the pawn on b4 would be defended already. However, with ...Nbd7 played instead of ...a5, our opponent is caught slightly off guard so the idea c3 can come immediately after Na2.  In this case, they have the ...Ba6 idea which equalizes easily:  9...b4  10.Na2  Ba6  11.c3  bxc3  12.Nxc3  Black is able to trade off the a6-bishop which was bad in the previous line. The knight is arguably better placed on b8 as well because it protects the c6-pawn and can recapture on a6 if needed. }
9... Nbd7 10. Bd3
{ While Black is aiming to take space on the queenside, White keeps the e4-break in sight. }
