[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 g6"]
[Black "1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 g6  – main line 4...Bg7 #5/11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4
{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... g6
{ 3...g6 is one of the most common moves against the Jobava London but it's important to note that this position can also be reached from the main line London:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  g6  . Many players that play the King’s Indian or Grunfeld tend to respond to the London this way. This gives White an opportunity to transpose into the Jobava with  3.Nc3  d5  4.e3  .  It is important to note this transposition, as most of the games from this starting position originated from the London. Therefore, 3...g6 should of course be considered a very serious challenge, but it's not as popular as 3...e6 or 3...c5.   White has many different options here but I'd like to keep things simple. White will generally proceed with the same common ideas. }
4. e3
{ 4.e3  maintains some degree of flexibility. Nb5 is in the air and h4-h5 is always an idea. }
4... Bg7 5. Nb5 Na6 6. h3
{ The point of h3 is to prevent any ...Nh5 ideas. Unfortunately, there are no crazy ideas with g4 in this position, the point is to force Black to make slight positional concessions and to finish development. }
6... O-O 7. Nf3
{ If White is not familiar with the ...Ne4 idea, it's easy to go wrong. } 7...
c6 8. Nc3
{ Black has to follow up c6 with extremely precise moves to fully equalize but White's play is still very natural. The good thing about 3. g6, is that White is able to play the same exact developing moves so there isn't much to memorize. }
8... Nc7
{ 8...Nc7 is very common in the database but it's not critical at all. You'll notice a common pattern where even top 10 players have no idea what they are doing here. }
9. Be2 Ne6 10. Be5
{ Yet again, the awkward placement of the knight on e6 makes the bishop on e5 very strong. }
10... b6 11. O-O Bb7
{ It is common to respond to ...b6 and ...Bb7 in these positions with a4 and a5! }
12. a4
{ a5 is sort of a positional threat. White's pieces coordinate well and the Bishop on e5 is extremely strong as it restricts Black's pieces quite well.   Note that  12.Nb1  also is a very interesting idea, improving the Knight. This backward maneuver is most commonly seen in the Bryer variation but it is also common in this opening. }
