[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4
{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... a6
{ I wouldn't say that 3...a6 is as directly challenging as other moves. However, it is very common among top-level grandmasters and makes for some really interesting chess.  The structures that we get here will be a bit different from the other positions because Nb5 is totally out of the question. Since the position will be closed in most outcomes, you can count on g4 and h4 being viable options. }
4. e3
{ This is the first major crossroad and Black's next move will dictate the dynamic of the position. }
4... c5
{ 4...c5 is just a worse version of 3...c5 @@StartBracket@@chapter 3@@EndBracket@@. I would regard this as directly critical but of course, some precision is required.   4...Bf5  5.Nf3  transposes to a position we have reached in chapter 1 after 3...a6. }
5. dxc5
{ The funny thing about this position is the  5...Nc6  is the most popular by far, then  5...e6  , and then  5...Qa5  .  5...Qa5  is the only move that is close to equality while  5...e6  and  5...Nc6  give White an edge. If that doesn't seem like an opportunity to catch your opponents, then I don't know what is. }
5... e6
{ This is a move that I have faced quite a lot in blitz but White is able to get a slightly better position with the bishop pair.  One should also note that 5...e6 is the second most popular move. It is very clear that after 4...c5, even top GMs are unaware of the theory. }
6. Na4 Nbd7
{ This has been played in a few games but no GMs on the black side. If Black prepares well, things can be very complex but from an objective perspective, White has an edge. }
7. b4 b6
{ 7...b6 is always critical in these structures because it is the most direct way to challenge the pawn chain. However, in most cases, Black is sacrificing a piece so I feel like the idea is difficult for humans to play from a practical perspective. }
8. c6 Bxb4+ 9. c3 Ba5 10. cxd7+ Bxd7
{ This is not the first time that we have seen b6 leading to a piece sacrifice. In this case, White has a slight advantage but must play accurately. }
11. Be5
{ The bishop on e5 is an all-star. It defends c3 and allows for White to continue developing. }
11... Qe7
{ 11...Qe7 is critical, it's important to put immediate pressure on the poorly-placed knight on a4. Castling immediately would give White enough time to develop. }
12. Qc2 O-O
{ The initiative continues for Black but White can consolidate with precise play! }
13. Nb2 { Here comes yet another ridiculous idea. } 13... Rac8
{ It's very difficult to explain why this is the best move without looking at the computer. The first question you ask yourself is 'why not Bxa6?'. ...Rfc8 is the most intuitive move if you intend to bring a rook to the c-file. However, Black has an absolutely beautiful rook sacrifice. }
14. Bxa6 Ng4 15. Bxc8 Rxc8
{ Black is down a full rook but White's king is still in the center and Black's pieces are all very active. }
16. Ne2 Nxe5 17. O-O
{ White had to give back the piece but still remains up the exchange. Despite Black's activity, White has an advantage and the material advantage will be valuable long term. }
