[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 a6"]
[Black "3.Bf4 a6 4.e3 e6 #1/16"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4
{ This is going to be the starting position of the Jobava London where Black begins to deviate. Black has many different possibilities here so it's important to be familiar with the different structures that arise.  The best part of the Jobava London for amateur players is its simplicity. After studying it in-depth and playing games, you'll find that the play is very natural. }
3... a6
{ I wouldn't say that 3...a6 is as directly challenging as other moves. However, it is very common among top-level grandmasters and makes for some really interesting chess.  The structures that we get here will be a bit different from the other positions because Nb5 is totally out of the question. Since the position will be closed in most outcomes, you can count on g4 and h4 being viable options. }
4. e3
{ This is the first major crossroad and Black's next move will dictate the dynamic of the position. }
4... e6
{ 4...e6 is the most common move and is in line with 3...a6. Black wants to play ...e6 without allowing the possibility of Nb5. This allows for some very interesting possibilities. I think you can already guess which move I am going to suggest...   4...Bf5  5.Nf3  transposes to a position we have reached in chapter 2 after 3...a6. }
5. g4
{ This idea of g4 is multi-faceted. White wants to play g5 to remove the knight from f6 and extend on the queenside. Additionally, the bishop can develop to g2. Think of it as an aggressive fianchetto. }
5... h6
{ I wouldn't say that 5...h6 is a bad move but 5...Bb4 is definitely the critical variation. }
6. h4
{ Black must immediately create counterplay on the queenside before they are overwhelmed on the kingside. }
6... c5
{ This is the most common move in the database and has been played by quite a few grandmasters, but it is actually a huge mistake and gives White a much better position. }
7. Qf3
{ I think that every time Qf3 is played it deserves an exclamation mark. This type of idea of bringing the queen out is so unique but still incredibly strong. White is preparing g5 and now castling is an option. }
7... Nc6 8. Nge2
{ White is ready to castle at any moment and the threat of g5 is always looming. }
8... cxd4 9. exd4 b5 10. g5 Ng8 11. O-O-O
{ Black must be extremely precise here to not simply get crushed. } 11... Qa5
12. gxh6 Nxh6 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Qxd5 Bb7 15. Bg2
{ Black's king is stuck in center. Let's see the only way to survive... } 15...
Be7 16. Rhe1 Rd8 17. Qb3 Bb4
{ You must voluntarily accept the discovered check... } 18. Nc3+ Kf8 19. d5 Ne7
20. Bg5 { The series of only moves keeps going. } 20... Bd6 21. Bxe7+ Bxe7 22.
d6 Rxd6 23. Bxb7 Nf5 24. Ne4 Rxd1+ 25. Rxd1
{ It seems like we've reached the end of the rainbow. After insane calculations and many only moves from Black, White still has an advantage. If another top grandmaster plays 6...c5, they will be punished severely. }
*

