{ 4...e6 is the most common move and is in line with 3...a6. Black wants to play ...e6 without allowing the possibility of Nb5. This allows for some very interesting possibilities. I think you can already guess which move I am going to suggest...   4...Bf5  5.Nf3  transposes to a position we have reached in chapter 2 after 3...a6. }
5. g4
{ This idea of g4 is multi-faceted. White wants to play g5 to remove the knight from f6 and extend on the queenside. Additionally, the bishop can develop to g2. Think of it as an aggressive fianchetto. }
5... c5
{ Interestingly enough, c5 is the most common move in the database but it actually gives White an advantage. This is another example of Top GMs having no clue what to do. }
6. g5 Nfd7 7. Qg4
{ I was the first to play this idea in the World Rapid and Blitz. I actually got an amazing position which I managed to throw away under time pressure. But this certainly was a great illustration of this move's power. }
7... Nc6 8. O-O-O b5 9. Qg3
{ We see the Qg3 motif repeated and Black is has a very difficult decision here. }
9... b4 { White sacrifices a piece on d5 again! } 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Bc7 Qe7 12.
Bg2
{ It is clear that Black is completely uncoordinated and the king is stuck in the center. This attack is very difficult to deal with and very easy for White to play. }
12... Ra7 13. Bxd5
{ If you can guess the best move here, you should quit your day job and become a chess professional. }
13... b3
{ I can't even begin to explain why this is the best move so I will just leave it here and conclude that Black is in big trouble. }
14. Bxb3
{ White maintains a huge attack and has 2 pawns for the piece while Black's position is discombobulated in every way possible. }
