5... Bb4 6. Ne2 O-O 7. a3 Be7 8. g5
{ This idea has been played by Carlsen and Firouzja; it's clearly an important theoretical battleground in the Jobava London. Things become extremely complicated here. }
8... Nfd7
{ Despite ...Nfd7 being significantly less common it is critical as well. There are multiple ways to proceed here but I prefer the most aggressive one! }
9. e4
{ e4 puts direct pressure in the center and forces Black to make a difficult position. It's very tempting to take the g5-pawn but this gives White amazing practical attacking chances. }
9... Bxg5 10. Rg1 Bxf4 11. Nxf4 Qh4 12. Qf3 Nc6 13. O-O-O
{ Despite being down a pawn White has the initiative and Black is behind in development. Things are extremely complex here but I think it is fair to conclude that White has amazing attacking chances. }
