{ 4...e6 is the most common move and is in line with 3...a6. Black wants to play ...e6 without allowing the possibility of Nb5. This allows for some very interesting possibilities. I think you can already guess which move I am going to suggest...   4...Bf5  5.Nf3  transposes to a position we have reached in chapter 2 after 3...a6. }
5. g4
{ This idea of g4 is multi-faceted. White wants to play g5 to remove the knight from f6 and extend on the queenside. Additionally, the bishop can develop to g2. Think of it as an aggressive fianchetto. }
5... Bb4 6. Ne2 O-O 7. a3 Be7 8. g5
{ This idea has been played by Carlsen and Firouzja; it's clearly an important theoretical battleground in the Jobava London. Things become extremely complicated here. }
8... Nh5 9. h4 Nxf4 10. Nxf4
{ This entire sequence is more or less forced as there is a big gap in the 1st and 2nd moves for Black. }
10... c5 11. Bd3
{ This is an extremely critical moment where Black must decide how to defend against White's attack.   11...f5  and  11...c4  are the 2 options. Both moves are equal but  11...c4  is much more forcing and was played by Wesley So. }
11... c4 12. Bxh7+ Kxh7 { The crazy sequences continues. } 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. g6
fxg6 15. Nxg6 Rf5 16. Qh8+ Kf7 17. Qh7
{ Wesley actually made a mistake here by playing  17...Bf6  .   17...Nc6  and  17...Nd7  both equalize but one should note that when you are playing the game, it is absolutely terrifying and you have no idea if the position is equal or not. }
17... Bf6
{ 17...Bf6 is a very logical defensive move but White can break through with brute force. }
18. Nh8+ Ke7 19. O-O-O Kd7 20. e4 { It is crucial to break everything open! }
20... dxe4 21. d5
{ White is continuing the initiative and making things very difficult for Black. From a practical perspective, this is very scary for Black and is likely to make many opponents panic. }
21... Qa5 22. Nxe4 Kc7
{ A sequence of 2 only moves, but Black is forced to be even more precise. One should note that I am playing the best defensive moves to show the degree of precision required to defend. }
23. Nxf6 Rxf6 24. Qxg7+ Nd7 25. Kb1
{ The forcing continuation still goes on after this, but the computer gives White a slight edge. I would certainly prefer to have White here. }
