1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. Bf4
{ Although it is very tempting to go in the French with  3.e4  , it is not in the purview of this course.   3.Bf4  leads to some very interesting complications and has the potential to transpose into main lines. }
3... Bb4 { 3...d5  would transpose to chapter 1: 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 e6. }
4. Qd3
{ White is ready to castle immediately. Black has many different setups here, which lead to very interesting positions. }
4... c5
{ 4...c5 has been played very few times but it is critical from a theoretical perspective as White must reply appropriately. }
5. dxc5 Na6 6. O-O-O Nxc5 7. Qd4 Qa5 8. Be5
{ This position leads to a slightly favorable endgame unless Black starts pawngrabbing... }
8... d5 9. a3 Bxc3 10. Qxc3 Qxc3 11. Bxc3 b6
{ These types of endgames give White a slight edge, as the c3-bishop is very powerful. }
