[White "8) 1.d4 d5 2.Nc3 e6 (And 2...Bf5 + 2...c5)"]
[Black "1.d4 d5 2.Nc3 c5 #1/16"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ The main move order that I have shown in the Jobava London is after  1...Nf6  . However,  1...d5  is another important order to consider. In most cases, it transposes, however, it is important to be aware of when it doesn't transpose. }
2. Nc3
{ I recommend this move order because the goal is to make sure that moves other than 2...Nf6 aren't optimal. }
2... c5
{ This isn't a very common move but it's critical to respond precisely. } 3. e4
{ It's crucial to break in the center! } 3... dxe4 4. d5 Nf6 5. Nge2
{ One should note that Nge2 is a completely new move and has only been played twice. This will certainly come as a very dangerous surprise. Black has a few different ways to develop. }
5... g6
{ This is a much simpler alternative to 5...e6 and leads to very natural development for Black. However, this isn't as directly challenging as 5...e6 and gives White a very slight edge. }
6. Ng3 Bg7 7. Ngxe4 Nxe4 8. Nxe4 O-O 9. Be2
{ There are a few different ways to develop but Black more or less has the same plan. }
9... Bf5 10. Ng3 Bc8
{ This is one of the top computer suggestions but I highly doubt any human will play this. Just in case, one should be aware of a very interesting idea. }
11. h4
{ If you thought that I was just going to castle, then you clearly haven't been paying attention to the themes of the course. }
11... Nd7 12. h5 Nf6 13. Bf3
{ White can actually just castle next and have a comfortable advantage. The knight on f6 isn't great at supporting the ...e6 break. }
