2... c5
{ This isn't a very common move but it's critical to respond precisely. } 3. e4
{ It's crucial to break in the center! } 3... dxe4 4. d5 Nf6 5. Nge2
{ One should note that Nge2 is a completely new move and has only been played twice. This will certainly come as a very dangerous surprise. Black has a few different ways to develop. }
5... e6 { This is the most natural move as it directly challenges the center. }
6. Nf4 exd5 7. Nfxd5 Nxd5 8. Qxd5 Qxd5 9. Nxd5 Bd6 10. Be3
{ White is still down a pawn but has the initiative. The e4-pawn is also very loose. }
10... Nc6 11. O-O-O f5 12. Nf4 Ke7 13. h4
{ Nh5 is next. Black is forced to make some very difficult moves to equalize. }
13... Rd8 14. Nh5 h6 15. Nxg7 f4 16. Rxd6
{ This idea is truly beautiful. White sacrifices the exchange for a bishop and pawn and if d6 is recaptured either way White has a comfortable advantage. The only way to equalize is to ignore the rook entirely. }
16... Kxd6 17. Bxf4+ Ke7 18. Be2
{ The two bishops are very strong and the h6-pawn is very weak. Black's pawn structure is in disarray. White has a slight advantage. }
