[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ The main move order that I have shown in the Jobava London is after  1...Nf6  . However,  1...d5  is another important order to consider. In most cases, it transposes, however, it is important to be aware of when it doesn't transpose. }
2. Nc3
{ I recommend this move order because the goal is to make sure that moves other than 2...Nf6 aren't optimal. }
2... e6
{ 2...e6  might be played by opponents who want to transpose into the French. I will never understand why someone would willingly want to transpose into the French... }
3. Bf4
{ As I've said before, this is not a French course and I will stay true to the Bf4, Nc3 setup. The most common move here is 3...Nf6 which transposes but I will also show how to react if Black responds differently. }
3... Bd6 4. e3 Bxf4 5. exf4
{ 5...Nf6  is the most common move by far but it's actually not accurate at all. Black needs to trade the c8-Bishop immediately as it is stuck behind the pawn chain. }
5... b6 6. Nf3 Ne7 7. g4
{ This move might look weird but it forces Black to make a difficult decision. There are many options, I will analyze the most logically. }
7... Ba6 8. Bxa6 Nxa6 9. h4
{ If White is allowed to play h5, then White will have a lot of space on the kingside and really restrict Black's pieces. However, playing ...h5 and the accurate moves after that is not easy. }
9... h5 10. gxh5 Rxh5 11. Ne5 g6 12. Qd3 Nb8
{ Black keeps on moving backwards and it feels like the tide is turning. } 13.
O-O-O
{ Despite White making positional concessions, Black's king is still in the center and prone to attack. }
