1. d4 f5
{ I couldn't make this a Lifetime Repertoire without going into the Dutch. I've personally never been afraid of the Dutch and I don't think you should be either. The Dutch is very uncommon for me to face in classical chess but I face it infrequently in online games.  I think I can safely say that the Dutch is not a direct challenge to the Jobava London but it's important to know how to play against it. There are many setups but I'm going to recommend one that has a similar developmental style. }
2. Nc3 { It wouldn't be a Jobava London without bringing the knight to c3. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4
{ You might think that we wouldn't go for the traditional setup but this is where we really get to have some fun. If you've been paying attention to the common themes, you might guess our next move. }
3... g6
{ Some Dutch players who are used to always bringing the bishop to g7 will land themselves in hot water as White has a very direct attack. }
4. h4 { White aims to play h5 and disrupt Black's development. } 4... Bg7
{ It's possible to go h5 immediately but we should be patient and prepare it. }
5. e3
{ We are still in theoretical waters here but the computer is already giving +1 and it's clear that Black is in trouble. The threat of h5 is looming and White has very natural development. I won't go into too much depth here, instead, will show the key ideas and how White can naturally proceed. }
5... d6 6. Bc4 { Preventing the king from castling, h5 is still looming. } 6...
h6 { Preparing to counter h5 with ...h6. } 7. Qf3
{ One of the reasons why I firmly believe that the Moke London should be a Lifetime Repertoire is that the same ideas truly appear throughout all types of openings. The queen coming to f3 and g3 is extremely common and effective.  Once you are able to recognize these patterns in varying positions, you'll start to develop a great intuitive feel for the opening! }
7... e6 8. Qg3 Kf7 9. O-O-O
{ White has basically completed development and has a great position. Black's king on f7 will be a target very soon and Black is still significantly behind in development. }
