2... Nf6 3. Bf4
{ You might think that we wouldn't go for the traditional setup but this is where we really get to have some fun. If you've been paying attention to the common themes, you might guess our next move. }
3... d5
{ 3...d5 is a very natural move and actually transposes to a position with over 500 games. However, we get to play yet another classic idea. }
4. Nb5
{ The Nb5 idea is as strong as it gets. This idea is played when their pawns are on g6 or e6 and the point is to force the knight to a6. In this case, the f5-pawn weakens Black's position. }
4... Na6 5. e3
{ You could even go to the chapter with 3...e6 and play the exact same moves but the pawn being on f5 instead of f7 gives White the e5-square which is a dominating outpost. }
5... e6 { 5...c6  6.Nc3  Nc7  7.Nf3  e6  transposes to the text move. } 6. Nf3
c6 7. Nc3
{ Black plays the moves ...a6 and ...c6 in basically every game, both lines usually end up transposing. }
7... Nc7 8. Bd3
{ White's position is absolutely amazing. The knight comes to e2, White castles and then plays c4. The knight on c7 is terrible. Once the dark-squared bishops are traded, the e5 outpost will be even stronger and the c8-bishop is stuck behind the pawn chain. }
