{ You might think that we wouldn't go for the traditional setup but this is where we really get to have some fun. If you've been paying attention to the common themes, you might guess our next move. }
3... a6
{ ...a6 looks pretty weird but the idea is to play ...d5 next and not give White the chance to play Nb5. However, I'm sure you can guess the next move. }
4. g4
{ I think that the catchphrase of the Jobava London should be 'If you can play g4, play it and don't look back'. }
4... fxg4 5. Qd2
{ The queen usually goes to d3 but in this case, the queen is better on it d2 as cannot be targeted easily and protects the bishop on f4. }
5... d5 6. O-O-O e6 7. h3
{ You'll notice that this h3 idea is especially effective after Black has played ...e6. We chose to develop first and wait for the c8-bishop to be closed before opening the position. I can conclude here that White has a strong initiative and will proceed with an attack on the kingside! }
