4. g4
{ I think that the catchphrase of the Jobava London should be 'If you can play g4, play it and don't look back'. }
4... d5
{ There was a game here between a GM and IM in August of 2021. Let's see how White should proceed. }
5. g5 Ne4 6. e3
{ Let me offer another structural way to understand the position:  Firstly, we should analyze the pawn structure. The g5-pawn is the first interesting point, it's clear that White has a space advantage and is free to extend further with h4-h5.Additionally, the d5-e6-f5 central structure creates a hole on e5.Furthermore, the extension of the f-pawn leaves the king potentially weak.  Therefore, the goal should be to retain positional control of the center while continuing to gain more space.   The premature capture  6.Nxe4  would restrict the development of the g1-knight after  6...fxe4  . White needs to bring the g1-knight out first! }
6... e6 7. Nxe4 fxe4 8. f3
{ The inclusion of e3 and ...e6 is a crucial tempo and now Black is faced with a very difficult dilemma. Capturing on f3 would help White's development and lead to a deadly image while ignoring the pawn would let White double and isolate the e-pawns. I can conclude here that White has positional control and a strong initiative. }
