{ This will definitely provoke an eyebrow raise or two. This idea might look crazy but it's actually the first choice of the engine. White aims to go for the immediate initiative, the g-pawn is a small price to pay.  There are a few logical ways for Black to respond but the ideas are pretty similar. }
4... Bb4
{ 4...Bb4 is the most common move in the database but that doesn't mean much as there have only been 3 games here. It's very logical, ignoring the g-pawn and prioritizing rapid development. }
5. gxf5 exf5
{ Simply recapturing is much more natural, but yet again this gives White a crucial tempo. }
6. Qd3
{ Black's development is simply too weak. Qd3 comes with tempo as the f5-pawn is under attack, White can castle next and then the kingside development follows quickly. Black is already in trouble and is forced to find difficult moves. }
6... Ne4
{ 6...Ne4 was played in 2 of the 3 games in the database.  One should note that this specific line is basically uncharted waters and I'm basically creating my own theory by choosing which moves to cover. This should not be something that's scary but rather encouraging.  The lack of games in the database, only ensures that you'll be significantly more familiar with the position and able to play comfortably while your opponent navigates the dangerous jungle that you've brought them into. }
7. O-O-O Bxc3 8. f3
{ Completely ignoring the bishop. One of Black's pieces will fall. } 8... Bxb2+
9. Kxb2 Nf6
{ Black can win a pawn but now White's lead in development will manifest into a crushing initiative. }
10. Nh3 O-O 11. Rg1
{ If you're going to play this line against the Dutch, you should get used to being down a pawn but rest assured that it really doesn't matter. }
11... Kh8 12. e4
{ I could go farther here but there isn't really much of a point. I think it's clear in this position that Black's entire queenside is dormant while White has a raging attack and initiative. }
