{ This will definitely provoke an eyebrow raise or two. This idea might look crazy but it's actually the first choice of the engine. White aims to go for the immediate initiative, the g-pawn is a small price to pay.  There are a few logical ways for Black to respond but the ideas are pretty similar. }
4... fxg4
{ This is arguably the most natural but White has a very nice idea here. } 5.
h3
{ This theme is quite common in chess. This reminds me of the Benko where Black gives up a pawn on ...b5 followed by ...a6. This allows White to open up the kingside and follow up the initiative. This idea is even stronger because the most natural responses are all very bad. }
5... gxh3
{ This is a very likely path, your unsuspecting opponent might see another juicy pawn and take it. The best response is to ignore it of course... }
6. Qd3
{ In classic Moke London fashion we bring the queen out and aim to castle queenside. The lead in development is already noticeable. Black intends to castle kingside but the entire kingside has been blown open so that certainly won't be ideal. }
6... Bb4 7. Nxh3 O-O
{ Black might castle and assume that everything is okay... } 8. Ng5 h6 9. Rxh6
{ Black has played pretty natural moves but somehow the game is over. } 9...
gxh6 10. Qg6+ Kh8 11. Qxh6+ Kg8 12. Qg6+ Kh8 13. O-O-O
{ The d1-rook will be the dagger. } 13... Qe7 14. Qh6+ Kg8 15. e3
{ White is down a rook temporarily but Black's entire queenside is dormant. }
15... Qg7 16. Qh1 Bd6 17. Bd3 Bxf4 18. exf4
{ Rg1 is next and Black is completely lost. } *

